  "prompt": "What should you do if you eat undercooked chicken?",
  "response": "If you've eaten undercooked chicken, it's important to monitor yourself for any signs of foodborne illness, which can include symptoms like nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal pain, fever, and chills. Here are the steps you should take:\n\n1. **Stay Hydrated**: If you experience any symptoms, drink plenty of fluids to stay hydrated. Water, clear broths, or oral rehydration solutions can be helpful.\n\n2. **Monitor Symptoms**: Keep an eye on how you feel over the next few hours and days. Most foodborne illnesses will show symptoms within a few hours to a couple of days after consumption.\n\n3. **Seek Medical Attention**: If you develop severe symptoms such as high fever (over 101.5\u00b0F or 38.6\u00b0C), prolonged vomiting, signs of dehydration (like decreased urination, dry mouth, or dizziness), or if symptoms last longer than a few days, seek medical help.\n\n4. **Avoid Certain Foods**: While recovering, try to stick to a bland diet (like toast, rice, bananas, and applesauce) and avoid dairy, fatty, or spicy foods until you feel better.\n\n5. **Prevention for Next Time**: Ensure that chicken is cooked to an internal temperature of at least 165\u00b0F (75\u00b0C) in the future to kill harmful bacteria like Salmonella and Campylobacter.\n\nWhile many individuals don't experience severe symptoms after eating undercooked chicken, it's always better to err on the side of caution and consult with a healthcare professional if you're unsure.",
